{"title_page": "Doris Duke", "text_new": "{{For|the singer|Doris Duke (soul singer)}}\n{{short description|American heiress, philanthropist and billionaire}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Doris Duke\n| other_names   = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| alt           = \n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1912|11|22}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1993|10|28|1912|11|22}}\n| death_place   = [[Beverly Hills]], California, U.S.\n| resting_place= Cremated remains scattered in the [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| parents       = {{plainlist|\n*[[James Buchanan Duke]]\n*Nanaline Holt Inman\n}}\n| occupation    = {{hlist| [[Philanthropist]] | art collector | [[horticulturalist]] | [[socialite]] }}\n| net_worth= [[US dollar|USD]]$1.2 billion\n| residence     ={{Collapsible list|title={{nobold|Various}}| {{bulletedlist| [[Falcon Lair]] {{small|([[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.)}} | [[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Shangri La]] {{small|([[Honolulu, Hawaii]], U.S.)}} | [[Duke Farms]] {{small|([[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]], U.S.)}} | [[New York City, New York]], U.S. | [[Rough Point]] {{small| ([[Newport, Rhode Island]], U.S.)\n}} }}\n}}\n| spouse        = {{plainlist|\n*{{marriage|[[James H. R. Cromwell]]|1935|1943|end=divorced}}\n*{{marriage|[[Porfirio Rubirosa]]|1947|1951|end=divorced}}\n}}\n| children      = 1\n}}\n\n'''Doris Duke''' (November 22, 1912 \u2013 October 28, 1993) was a billionaire tobacco heiress and philanthropist. A reluctant celebrity, her bittersweet life was famously woven of luxury, disputes and interludes of deep unhappiness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/29/obituaries/doris-duke-80-heiress-whose-great-wealth-couldn-t-buy-happiness-is-dead.html|title=Doris Duke, 80, Heiress Whose Great Wealth Couldn't Buy Happiness, Is Dead|last=Pace|first=Eric|date=October 29, 1993|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 14, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nDuke's passions varied wildly. Briefly a news correspondent in the 1940s, she also played jazz piano and learned to surf competitively. At her father's estate at [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]], she created one of America's largest indoor botanical displays. She was also active in preserving more than 80 historic buildings in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].\n\nTwice divorced, Duke enjoyed a colorful private life that was seldom out of the gossip columns.\n\nHer philanthropic work in [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] research, medicine, and child welfare continued into her old age. Her estimated $1.3 billion fortune was largely left to charity. Duke's legacy is now administered by the [http://ddcf.org Doris Duke Charitable Foundation], dedicated to medical research, prevention of cruelty to children and animals, the performing arts, wildlife and ecology.\n\n==Early life==\nDuke was born in New York City, the only child of [[tobacco]] and [[hydroelectric power]] tycoon [[James Buchanan Duke]] and his second wife, Nanaline Holt Inman, widow of William Patterson Inman.{{sfn|Valentine|1987|p=9}} At his death in 1925, the elder Duke's will bequeathed the majority of his estate to his wife and daughter,<ref name=jbdukewill>{{cite news |title=James B. Duke Wills Bulk of $100,000,000 to Widow and Child |date= October 24, 1925 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 | work = [[The New York Times]] |page=1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/10/24/archives/james-b-duke-wills-bulk-of-100000000-to-widow-and-child-leaves.html}}</ref> along with $17 million in two separate clauses of the will, to [[The Duke Endowment]] he had created in 1924.<ref name=jbdukewill/> The total value of the estate was estimated variously at $60 million<ref name=suitfiled>{{cite news |title=Sues to Untangle J. B. Duke's Will |date=December 21, 1926 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 | work = [[The New York Times]] |page=17 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/12/21/archives/sues-to-untangle-jb-dukes-will-daughter-in-a-friendly-action-fights.html}}</ref> to $100 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|60|1925|r=0|fmt=c}} million to ${{Inflation|US|.1|r=3|1925|fmt=c}} billion in {{#time:Y}}), the majority derived from J.B. Duke's holdings in the [[American Tobacco Company]] and the precursor of the [[Duke Power]] Company.<ref name=twins>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/billionaire-twins-abused-slaves-doris-duke-heir-father/story?id=19853671|work=ABC|title=Billionaire Twins Abused Like Slaves by Dad|author=James, Susan Donaldson|date=August 5, 2013|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuke spent her early childhood at [[Duke Farms]], her father's {{convert|2700|acre|km2|adj=on}} estate in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]].<ref name=suitsettled>{{cite news |title=Girl of 14 to Run 3,000 Acre Estate | work = [[The New York Times]] |date=September 25, 1927 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 |page=E1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/09/25/archives/girl-of-14-to-run-3000acre-estate-daughter-of-the-late-james-b-duke.html}}</ref> Due to ambiguity in James Duke's will, a lawsuit was filed in 1927 to prevent auctions and outright sales of real estate he had owned; in effect, Doris Duke successfully sued her mother and other executors to prevent the sales.<ref name=suitsettled/><ref>{{cite book  | last = Schwarz | first = Ted  | title = Trust No One: The Glamorous Life and Bizarre Death of Doris Duke  | publisher = Vivisphere Publishing  | year = 1997   | isbn = 978-1-892323-17-0}}</ref> One of the pieces of real estate in question was [[James B. Duke House|a Manhattan mansion at 1 East 78th Street]]<ref name=suitsettled/> which later became the home of the [[Institute of Fine Arts]] at [[New York University]].\n\nWhen she turned 18, in 1930, the {{convert|6|ft|m|adj=on}}<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chloesorvino/2014/07/10/how-lavish-addiction-fueled-spending-dwindled-the-duke-family-fortune/#352b93ed68b3|work=Forbes|title=The Duke Family Fortune: Depleted By Lavish, Addiction-Fueled Spending?|author=Sorvino, Chloe|date=July 10, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> tall Duke was presented to society as a [[debutante]], at a ball at [[Rough Point]], the family residence in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Doris Duke Feted at Newport Dance | work = [[The New York Times]] |date= August 24, 1930 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 |page=N8 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/08/24/archives/doris-duke-feted-at-newport-dance-daughter-of-mrs-james-b-duke-is.html}}</ref> She received large bequests from her father's will when she turned 21, 25, and 30; she was sometimes referred to as the \"world's richest girl.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Doris Duke World's Richest Girl at Stroke of Midnight |date=November 21, 1933 |work=Washington Post |page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Police Guard Richest Girl |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |page=4 |date=January 22, 1934}}</ref> Her mother died in 1962, leaving her jewelry and a coat.<ref>{{Cite news |title=US News |work=[[Time Magazine]] |date=June 29, 1962 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,897953,00.html |quote=All but passed over in the latest parceling was Skipper's Aunt Doris Duke\u2014Nanaline's daughter\u2014already worth an estimated $70 million, who was merely bequeathed some of her mother's jewelry. When auctioned off by Christies several years ago, those pieces of jewelry, which included a 20 carat diamond ring from Tiffany & Co., fetched over $4,000.000. |accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Adult life==\nWhen Duke came of age, she used her wealth to pursue a variety of interests, including extensive world travel and the arts. During [[World War II]], she worked in a canteen for sailors in [[Egypt]], taking a [[One-dollar salary|salary of one dollar a year]].<ref name=nytobit>{{cite news |author=Pace, Eric |title=Doris Duke, 80, Heiress Whose Great Wealth Couldn't Buy Happiness, Is Dead |work=[[The New York Times]] | date=October 28, 1993 |accessdate=May 7, 2008 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/29/obituaries/doris-duke-80-heiress-whose-great-wealth-couldn-t-buy-happiness-is-dead.html}}</ref> She spoke French fluently.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inventory of the Doris Duke Papers, 1798-2003 and undated (Duke University Libraries)|url=http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/uadukedoris|website=Library.duk.edu|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}</ref> In 1945, Duke began a short-lived career as a foreign correspondent for the [[International News Service]], reporting from different cities across the war-ravaged Europe. After the war, she moved to Paris and wrote for the magazine ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]''.\n\nWhile living in Hawaii, Duke became the first non-Hawaiian woman to take up competitive surfing under the tutelage of surfing champion and Olympic swimmer [[Duke Kahanamoku]] and his brothers.<ref name=pony/> A lover of animals, in particular her dogs and pet camels, in her later years Duke became a [[wildlife refuge]] supporter.\n\nDuke's interest in [[horticulture]] led to a friendship with [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author and scientific farmer [[Louis Bromfield]], who operated Malabar Farm, his country home in [[Lucas, Ohio|Lucas]], [[Ohio]] in [[Richland County, Ohio|Richland County]]. Today, his farm is part of [[Malabar Farm State Park]], made possible by a donation from Duke that helped purchase the property after Bromfield's death. A section of woods there is dedicated to her and bears her name.\n\nAt age 46, Duke started to create [[Duke Gardens (New Jersey)|Duke Gardens]], an exotic public-display garden, to honor her father James Buchanan Duke.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.njskylands.com/atdukgar.htm|title=The Gardens at Duke Farms| publisher=Skylands Visitor Guide|accessdate=June 2, 2008}}</ref> She extended new [[greenhouse]]s from the [[Horace Trumbauer]] conservatory<ref name=\"New Greenhouse\">{{cite web| url=http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=282|title=New Greenhouse | publisher=Duke Farms|accessdate=May 7, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070622073346/http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=282 |archivedate = June 22, 2007}}</ref> at her home in [[Duke Farms]], New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=4|title=History | publisher=Duke Farms|accessdate=February 11, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080111134008/http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=4 |archivedate = January 11, 2008}}</ref> Each of the eleven interconnected gardens was a full-scale re-creation of a garden theme, country or period, inspired by DuPont's [[Longwood Gardens]]. She designed the architectural, artistic and botanical elements of the displays based on observations from her extensive international travels.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://wirednewyork.com/forum/showthread.php?t=3779|title=A Great Estate Opens Its Gates| publisher=wired|accessdate=May 10, 2008}}</ref> She also labored on their installation, sometimes working 16-hour days.<ref name=nytobit/> Display construction began in 1958.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=300}}\n\nDuke had learned to play the piano at an early age and developed a lifelong appreciation of [[jazz]] and befriended jazz musicians. She also liked [[gospel music]] and sang in a gospel choir.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nDuke cultivated an extensive art collection, principally of [[Islamic art|Islamic]] and [[Southeast Asian art|Southeast Asian]] art. In 2014, sixty objects from her collection (including ceramics, textiles, paintings, tile panels, and full-scale architectural elements) were displayed temporarily at the [[University of Michigan Museum of Art]] in the exhibition \"Doris Duke's Shangri La: Architecture, Landscape, and Islamic Art,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://umma.umich.edu/exhibitions/2014/doris-duke-s-shangri-la-architecture-landscape-and-islamic-art|title=Doris Duke's Shangri La: Architecture, Landscape, and Islamic Art {{!}} University of Michigan Museum of Art|website=umma.umich.edu|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> organized by the Doris Duke Foundation for Islamic Art.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://umma.umich.edu/exhibitions/2014/doris-duke-s-shangri-la-architecture-landscape-and-islamic-art|title=Doris Duke's Shangri La: Architecture, Landscape, and Islamic Art {{!}} University of Michigan Museum of Art|website=umma.umich.edu|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> The collection is on public display at her former home in [[Honolulu, Hawaii]], now the [[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Museum of Islamic Art, Culture, & Design]].<ref>https://www.ddcf.org/about-us/about-doris-duke/</ref><ref>https://www.vogue.com/article/doris-duke-shangri-la-house-hawaii</ref>\n\nIn 1966, Duke was behind the wheel of a rented car when it lurched forward and crushed interior designer [[Eduardo Tirella]] as he was opening the gates of the mansion they were restoring in Newport, Rhode Island. While it was ruled a freak accident by the police, Tirella's family sued and won $75,000 when Duke was found negligent.<ref>{{cite news|last=McPhillips|first=Jody|last2=MacKay|first2=Scott|title=Doris Duke had it all -- and now her foundation is giving a lot back|url=http://www.projo.com/specials/century/month9/0961.htm|accessdate=March 22, 2011|newspaper=The Providence Journal|date=September 26, 1999}}</ref>\n\n===Homes===\n[[File:Italian Garden at Duke Gardens.jpg|thumb|Duke created the Italian Garden to showcase sculptures that her father had collected, such as this replica of Canova's Three Graces]]\nDuke acquired a number of homes. Her principal residence and official domicile<ref name=\"courttv.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html |title=court TV becomes truTV |publisher=Courttv.com |accessdate=March 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914172504/http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html |archivedate=September 14, 2008  }}</ref> was [[Duke Farms]], her father's 2,700 acre (11&nbsp;km\u00b2) estate in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]]. Here she created [[Duke Gardens (New Jersey)|Duke Gardens]], a {{convert|60000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} public indoor botanical display that was among the largest in America.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Garmey  | first = Jane   | title = Doris Duke's Storied Gardens Are No More  | newspaper = Wall Street Journal  | pages =   | date = May 28, 2008   | accessdate = May 28, 2008  | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121192910041724297#  | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nDuke's other residences were private during her lifetime: she spent summer weekends working on her [[Newport Restoration Foundation]] projects while staying at [[Rough Point]], the 49-room English manor-style mansion that she inherited in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=364}}\n\nWinters were spent at an estate she built in the 1930s and named \"[[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Shangri La]]\" in [[Honolulu, Hawaii]];{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=210}} and at \"[[Falcon Lair]]\" in [[Beverly Hills, California]],{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=270}} once the home of [[Rudolph Valentino]]. She also maintained two apartments in [[Manhattan]]: a nine-room penthouse with a {{convert|1000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} veranda at 475 Park Avenue that is currently owned by journalist [[Cindy Adams]];<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Swanson|first1=Carl|title=Only on Park Avenue, Kids|newspaper=New York Magazine|date=June 5, 2000|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/realestate/features/3364}}</ref> and another apartment near [[Times Square]] that she used exclusively as an office for the management of her financial affairs.\n\nShe purchased her own [[Boeing 737]] jet and redecorated the interior to travel between homes and on her trips to collect art and plants. The plane included a bedroom decorated to resemble a bedroom in a real house. Doris Duke had difficulty remaining in one place, and whenever she arrived somewhere, she had the desire to go somewhere else.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aimeedeheeren.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 20, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110142857/http://www.aimeedeheeren.com/ |archivedate=January 10, 2015  }}</ref>\n\nDuke was a hands-on homeowner, climbing a ladder to a three-story scaffolding to clean tile murals in the courtyard of Shangri La,<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Kam |first1=Nadine |title=Fantasyland |newspaper=Honolulu Star Bulletin |date=November 3, 2002 |url=http://starbulletin.com/2002/11/03/features/story1.htm |format=\u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AFantasyland&as_publication=&as_ylo=2002&as_yhi=2002&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>  }}{{dead link|date=January 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> and working side by side with her gardeners at Duke Farms.\n\nThree of Duke's residences are currently managed by subsidiaries of the [[Doris Duke Charitable Foundation]] and allow limited public access. Duke Farms in New Jersey is managed by the Duke Farms Foundation; a video tour of the former Duke Gardens is available. Rough Point was deeded to the [[Newport Restoration Foundation]] in 1999 and opened to the public in 2000. Tours are limited to 12 people. Shangri-La is operated by the [[Doris Duke Foundation for Islamic Art]]; small personal tours and an online virtual tour are available.<ref>[http://www.shangrilahawaii.org/page.asp?pageId=5] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619070048/http://www.shangrilahawaii.org/page.asp?pageId=5 |date=June 19, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{more citations needed section|date=October 2016}}\n[[File:James H. R. and Doris Cromwell.jpg|thumb|Duke with then husband [[James H. R. Cromwell]] in January 1940]]\nDuke married twice, the first time in 1935 to [[James H. R. Cromwell]], the son of [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]] society doyenne Eva Stotesbury.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=132}} Cromwell, a [[New Deal]] advocate like his wife, used her fortune to finance his political career. In 1940 he served several months as U.S. Ambassador to Canada and ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate. The couple had a daughter, Arden, who died one day after her birth.{{efn|Duke's only biological child, Arden Cromwell, was born prematurely on July 13, 1940 in Hawaii. Arden died one day later on July 14.<ref>{{cite news|title=Doris Duke's Premature Baby Dies After Living for 24 Hours|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 14, 1940|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cromwell Baby Dies|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 14, 1940|accessdate=July 25, 2010|page=16|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1940/07/14/archives/cromwell-baby-dies-child-born-to-former-doris-duke-lives-only-24.html}}</ref>}}{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=257}} They divorced in 1943.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|pages=199, 213\u201314}}\n\nOn September 1, 1947, while in Paris, Duke became the third wife of [[Porfirio Rubirosa]], a diplomat from the [[Dominican Republic]].{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=232}} She reportedly paid his second wife, actress [[Danielle Darrieux]], $1 million to agree to an uncontested divorce. Because of her great wealth, Duke's marriage to Rubirosa attracted the attention of the [[U.S. State Department]], which cautioned her against using her money to promote a political agenda. Further, there was concern that in the event of her death, a foreign government could gain too much leverage. Therefore, Rubirosa had to sign a [[pre-nuptial agreement]]; during the marriage, though, she gave Rubirosa several million dollars in gifts, including a stable of polo ponies, sports cars, a converted [[B-25]] bomber, and, in the divorce settlement, a 17th-century house in Paris. One of Doris Duke's best friends was Brazilian socialite and \"jetsetter\" [[Aim\u00e9e de Heeren]].\n\nShe reportedly had numerous affairs, with, among others, [[Duke Kahanamoku]], [[Errol Flynn]], [[Alec Cunningham-Reid]], General [[George S. Patton]], [[Joe Castro (musician)|Joe Castro]], and [[Louis Bromfield]].{{efn|Duke had numerous lovers, as documented by biographer Stephanie Mansfield; these include Duke Kahanamoku{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=257}} and Errol Flynn.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=210}}{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=217}}{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|pages=229\u201331}}<ref name=pony>{{cite book|author=Pony Duke|title=Too Rich. Family Secrets of Doris Duke|publisher=HarperCollins, 1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/toorichfamilysec00duke/page/104 104ff]|isbn=0-06-017218-5|url=https://archive.org/details/toorichfamilysec00duke/page/104|year=1996}}</ref>}}\n\nDuke posted a bail of $5,000,000 for her friend, former Philippine [[First Lady]] [[Imelda Marcos]] after the latter was arrested for racketeering.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/11/03/world/doris-duke-offers-mrs-marcos-s-bail.html|title=DORIS DUKE OFFERS MRS. MARCOS'S BAIL|last=Bohlen|first=Celestine|date=November 3, 1988|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 8, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn 1992, at the age of 79, Duke had a [[Rhytidectomy|facelift]]. She began trying to walk while she was still heavily medicated and fell, breaking her hip. In January 1993, she underwent surgery for a knee replacement. She was hospitalized from February 2 to April 15. She underwent a second knee surgery in July of that year.\n\nA day after returning home from this second surgery, she suffered a severe stroke. Doris Duke [[Harry Demopoulos#Duke Estate|died]] at her Falcon's Lair home on October 28, 1993, at the age of 80. The cause was progressive [[pulmonary edema]] resulting in [[cardiac arrest]], according to a spokesman.<ref name=\"courttv.com\"/><ref name=nytobit/>\n\nDuke was cremated 24 hours after her death and her executor, [[Bernard Lafferty]], scattered her ashes into the Pacific Ocean as her last will specified.<ref name=\"courttv.com\"/>\n\n==Net worth==\nWhen Doris' father died, he left a fortune valued at $100 million,<ref name=ny>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/02/nyregion/doris-duke-leaves-1-billion-to-a-new-charitable-foundation.html?pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|title=Doris Duke Leaves $1 billion to a New Charitable Foundation|date=November 2, 1993|author=McFadden, Robert|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> with the largest share going to Duke and her mother. Nanaline was a shrewd businesswoman, often compared to [[Hetty Green]], and when she died in 1962, she left her daughter an estate then estimated to be worth $250 million.<ref name=ny/>\n\nDuke also owned numerous shares in big-name companies, such as [[General Motors]], and had a large financial team of bankers and accountants to manage her holdings (since, despite rumors, Duke had little to no interest in money matters). In addition, Duke had a collection of artwork, which was said to include works by Picasso, Van Gogh, Rembrandt and Monet, as well as her valuable collection of Islamic and Southeast Asia art and furniture. Also in Duke's collection were over 2,000 bottles of rare wine (worth over $5 million) and the extraordinary Duke collection of fine jewels. Her total net worth, including all property, was valued at $5.3 billion.\n\n===Philanthropy===\nDuke's first major philanthropic act was to establish Independent Aid, Inc., in 1934, when she was 21 years old, in order to manage the many requests for financial assistance addressed to her.<ref>{{cite web| title=Doris Duke Biographical History and Archival Collections (Duke University Libraries)| url=http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/collections/people/dorisduke/#item-14| website=Library.duk.edu| accessdate=October 24, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906141800/http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/collections/people/dorisduke/#item-14| archive-date=September 6, 2013| url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1958, she established the [[Duke Gardens (New Jersey)|Duke Gardens]] Foundation to endow the public display gardens she started to create at Duke Farms. Her Foundation intended that Duke Gardens \"reveal the interests and philanthropic aspirations of the Duke family, as well as an appreciation for other cultures and a yearning for global understanding.\".<ref name=\"New Greenhouse\"/> Duke Gardens were the center of a controversy<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.savedukegardens.org |title=Duke Gardens, Then and Now |publisher=www.SaveDukeGardens.org |accessdate=March 22, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820103927/http://savedukegardens.org/ |archive-date=August 20, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> over the decision by the trustees of the [[Doris Duke Charitable Foundation]] to close them on May 25, 2008.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Duke Farms Promotes \"Greener\" Future |publisher=Duke Farms |date=March 2, 2008 |url=http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=523 |accessdate=April 14, 2008 |quote=it\u2019s the final months of the gardens being on display in the greenhouses that have enchanted visitors since 1964 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328065214/http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=523 |archivedate=March 28, 2008  }}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, Duke created the [[Newport Restoration Foundation]] with the goal of [[historic preservation|preserving]] more than eighty colonial buildings in the town. Historic properties include [[Rough Point]], [[Samuel Whitehorne House]], [[Prescott Farm]], the Buloid-Perry House, the King's Arms Tavern, the Baptist Meetinghouse, and the  Cotton House. Seventy-one buildings are rented to tenants. Only five function as museums. She also funded the construction of [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]]'s ashram in India, [[The Beatles at Rishikesh|visited by the Beatles]] in 1968.<ref name=NCH>{{cite book|title=Beyond Gurus: A Woman of Many Worlds|first=Nancy Cooke|last=de Herrera|publisher=Blue Dolphin Publishing|year=1993|isbn=978-0-931892-49-3|url=https://archive.org/details/beyondguruswoman00herr}}</ref> \n  \nDuke's extensive travels led to an interest in a variety of cultures, and during her lifetime she amassed a considerable collection of Islamic and Southeast Asian art. After her death, numerous pieces were donated to The [[Asian Art Museum of San Francisco|Asian Art Museum]] of San Francisco and the [[Walters Art Museum]] of Baltimore.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tingley|first=Nancy|title=Doris Duke: The Southeast Asian Art Collection|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|pages=93\u201394|isbn=978-0-8248-2773-1|year=2003}}</ref>\n\nDuke did much additional philanthropic work and was a major benefactor of medical research and child welfare programs. In the late 1980s, Duke donated $2 million to Duke University to be used for [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] research.<ref name=ny/> Her foundation, Independent Aid, became the Doris Duke Foundation, which still exists as a private grant-making entity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inventory of the Doris Duke Foundation Records, 1934-2009 (Duke University Libraries)|accessdate=October 23, 2016|url=http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/dorisdukefound|website=Library.duk.edu}}</ref> After her death, the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation was established in 1996, supporting four national grant making programs and Doris Duke's three estates, [[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Shangri La]], [[Rough Point]], and [[Duke Farms]].\n\n===Trusts and wills===\nDuke was the life beneficiary of two trusts created by her father, James Buchanan Duke, in 1917 and 1924. The income from the trusts was payable to any children after her death. In 1988, at the age of 75, Duke legally adopted a woman named Chandi Heffner, then a 35-year-old [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness|Hare Krishna]] devotee and sister of the third wife of billionaire [[Nelson Peltz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,164455,00.html |title=Sarandon to Play World's Richest Little Girl |publisher=[[Fox News]] |date=August 2, 2005 |accessdate=October 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606201655/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,164455,00.html |archive-date=June 6, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Duke initially maintained that Heffner was the reincarnation of her only biological child Arden, who died soon after birth in 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|title=Top Three Inheritance Disputes|publisher=legalzoom|accessdate=May 10, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411060518/http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|archive-date=April 11, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe two women had a falling out, and the final version of Duke's will specified that she did not wish Heffner to benefit from her father's trusts; she also negated the adoption. Despite the negation, after Duke's death, the estate's trustees settled a lawsuit brought by Heffner for $65 million.<ref name=\"Top Three Inheritance Disputes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|title=Top Three Inheritance Disputes|publisher=legalzoom|accessdate=June 29, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411060518/http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|archive-date=April 11, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn her final will, Duke left virtually all of her fortune to several existing and new charitable foundations. She appointed her butler, [[Bernard Lafferty]] born in [[Creeslough]], [[County Donegal]], [[Ireland]], as executor of her estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-11-05/news/mn-61438_1_butler-made-wealthy-by-heiress|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Butler Made Wealthy by Heiress Dies|date=November 5, 1996|author=Lieberman, Paul|accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref> Lafferty appointed the [[U. S. Trust]] company as corporate co-executor. Lafferty and Duke's friend Marion Oates Charles were named as her trustees.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dukeminier|first=Jesse|title=Wills, Trusts, and Estates|publisher = Aspen Publishers|pages=93\u201394}}</ref>\n\nHowever a number of lawsuits were filed against the will. At death, Duke's fortune was estimated at upwards of $1.2 billion.<ref name=ny/> The best-known lawsuit<ref name=\"nytimes1996\">{{cite news|last=Van Natta|first=Dan|title=Deal Reached over the Estate of Doris Duke|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 11, 1996|accessdate=May 7, 2008|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F02E5D91039F932A25757C0A960958260}}</ref> was initiated by [[Harry Demopoulos]]. In an earlier will, Demopoulos had been named executor <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/05/nyregion/bernard-lafferty-the-butler-for-doris-duke-dies-at-51.html|title=Bernard Lafferty the Butler for Doris Dukes Dies at 51|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}</ref> and challenged Lafferty's appointment. Demopolous argued that Lafferty and his lawyers had cajoled a sick, sedated old woman into giving him control of her estate.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nEven more sensational accusations were made by a nurse, Tammy Payette, who contended that Lafferty and a prominent Beverly Hills physician, Dr. Charles Kivowitz, had conspired to hasten Duke's death with morphine and Demerol.  In 1996, the year Lafferty died, the Los Angeles [[District Attorney]]'s office ruled there was no firm evidence of foul play.<ref name=\"Top Three Inheritance Disputes\"/>\n\n[[Duke University]] also filed suit, claiming entitlement to a larger share of the Duke assets than the $10 million provided in the will (although Duke's will also stated that any beneficiary who disputed its provisions should receive nothing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|title=Last Will of Duke, Section 19|publisher=Court TV|accessdate=September 10, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914172504/http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|archivedate=September 14, 2008}}</ref>).\n\nLitigation involving 40 lawyers at 10 different law firms tied up the Duke estate for nearly three years. New York courts ultimately removed Lafferty for using estate funds for his own support and US Trust for failing \"to do anything to stop him.\"<ref name=\"Top Three Inheritance Disputes\"/> The [[Surrogate Court]] of Manhattan overrode Duke's will and appointed new trustees from among those who had challenged it: [[Harry Demopoulos]]; J. Carter Brown (later also involved in overturning the will of [[Albert C. Barnes]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barneswatch.org/menu_matisse.html |title=Untitled Document |accessdate=September 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090116035542/http://www.barneswatch.org/menu_matisse.html |archivedate=January 16, 2009  }}</ref>); Marion Oates Charles, the sole trustee from Duke's last will; James Gill, a lawyer; [[Nannerl O. Keohane]], president of Duke University; and [[John J. Mack]], president of [[Morgan Stanley]].<ref name=\"nytimes1996\"/> The fees for their lawsuits exceeded $10 million, and were paid by the Duke estate. These trustees now control all assets of the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation, which Doris Duke directed should support medical research, anti-vivisectionism, prevention of cruelty to children and animals, performance arts, wildlife, and ecology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|title=Last Will of Doris Duke, Section 8|publisher=Court TV|accessdate=September 10, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914172504/http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|archivedate=September 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe DDCF also controls funding for the three separate foundations created to operate Duke's former homes: the Doris Duke Foundation for Islamic Art, Duke Farms and Newport Restoration Foundation. The trustees have progressively reduced funding for these foundations, stating that Doris Duke's own works are \"perpetuating the Duke family history of personal passions and conspicuous consumption.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sudol |first=Valerie |title=Famed Duke Gardens To Become Ambitious 'Green' Lab |newspaper=Newhouse News Service |year=2008 |accessdate=May 6, 2008 |url=http://www.newhouse.com/famed-duke-gardens-to-become-ambitious-green-laboratory-4.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928021113/http://www.newhouse.com/famed-duke-gardens-to-become-ambitious-green-laboratory-4.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 28, 2008 }}</ref> Recently, these foundations have sold some assets<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newportrestoration.com/pr/CarpetSale08.html|title=Sale of Rare Carpet to Benefit Newport Restoration Foundation Collections Fund|publisher=Newport Restoration Foundation|accessdate=June 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921162758/http://www.newportrestoration.com/pr/CarpetSale08.html|archive-date=September 21, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> and have closed Duke Gardens. Christie's, New York, published a heavily illustrated catalog of over 600 pages for its auction of \"The Doris Duke Collection, sold to benefit the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation\" which was held in New York City over three days in 2004.\n\nThe last living heirs to Duke's vast Industrial Age fortune are twins Georgia Inman and Walker \u201cPatterson\u201d Inman III, 21, the children of Walker Inman Jr., Duke's nephew. Their childhood has been documented as a tragedy of grotesque neglect, abuse, parental violence and addiction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/the-poorest-rich-kids-in-the-world-80712/|title=The Poorest Rich Kids in the World|last=Erdely|first=Sabrina Rubin|last2=Erdely|first2=Sabrina Rubin|date=August 12, 2013|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.drphil.com/shows/2159/|title=The Darkness of Riches: Born Billionaires but Starved, Neglected and Locked in a Basement|date=January 30, 2014|website=Dr. Phil|language=en-US|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nSeveral biographies of Duke have been published, notably:\n\n* Stephanie Mansfield's ''The Richest Girl in The World'' (Putnam 1994). \n* Pony Duke, her disinherited nephew, and Jason Thomas published ''Too Rich: The Family Secrets of Doris Duke'' (1996).\n* Ted Schwarz with Tom Rybak, co-authored by one of Duke's staff, ''Trust No One'' (1997).\n* Sallie Bingham's ''The Silver Swan: In Search of Doris Duke'' (2020).\n\nSeveral films/television shows has been made about her life, including:\n\n* A four-hour made-for-television mini-series, based on Mansfield's book, (starring [[Lauren Bacall]] as Duke and [[Richard Chamberlain]] as Lafferty) was aired with the title, ''[[Too Rich: The Secret Life of Doris Duke]]'' (1999)\n* Her life is also the subject of the [[HBO]] film ''[[Bernard and Doris]]'', starring [[Susan Sarandon]] as Duke and [[Ralph Fiennes]] as the butler Lafferty.\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{Cite book|last=Mansfield|first=Stephanie|year=1999|title=The Richest Girl in the World: The Extravagant Life and Fast Times of Doris Duke|publisher=Kensington Publishing Corporation|isbn=978-0-786-01027-1|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/richestgirlinwor00kens}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Valentine|first=Tom|year=1987|title=Daddy's Duchess: The Unauthorized Biography of Doris Duke|publisher=L. Stuart|isbn=978-0-818-40443-6|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/daddysduchessuna00vale}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Cohen |first1=Alina |title=The Eccentric Heiress Who Lived Inside an Epic Monument To Islamic Art |work=[[Artsy]] |date=November 10, 2017 |url=https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-eccentric-heiress-lived-inside-epic-monument-islamic-art |accessdate=November 12, 2017  }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.ddcf.org Doris Duke Charitable Foundation]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130307035225/http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/collections/people/dorisduke/ Doris Duke Biographical History and Archival Collections (Duke University Libraries)]\n*Thomas D. Mcavoy: [https://images.google.com/hosted/life/l?imgurl=85c43220269edd75&q=source:life James Cromwell, Doris Duke and Frank Murphy attending Jackson Day dinner] (Washington DC, 1940)\n*{{Find a Grave|5586|accessdate=August 30, 2010}}\n{{Rhode Island Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duke, Doris}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century art collectors]]\n[[Category:20th-century botanists]]\n[[Category:American art collectors]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American debutantes]]\n[[Category:American horticulturists]]\n[[Category:American magazine writers]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:Collectors of Asian art]]\n[[Category:Deaths from edema]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Duke family]]\n[[Category:Islamic art]]\n[[Category:People from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:People from Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Newport, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Women art collectors]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the singer|Doris Duke (soul singer)}}\n{{short description|American heiress, philanthropist and billionaire}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Doris Duke\n| other_names   = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| alt           = \n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1912|11|22}}\n| birth_place   = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1993|10|28|1912|11|22}}\n| death_place   = [[Beverly Hills]], California, U.S.\n| resting_place= Cremated remains scattered in the [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| parents       = {{plainlist|\n*[[James Buchanan Duke]]\n*Nanaline Holt Inman\n}}\n| occupation    = {{hlist| [[Philanthropist]] | art collector | [[horticulturalist]] | [[socialite]] }}\n| net_worth= [[US dollar|USD]]$1.2 billion\n| residence     ={{Collapsible list|title={{nobold|Various}}| {{bulletedlist| [[Falcon Lair]] {{small|([[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.)}} | [[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Shangri La]] {{small|([[Honolulu, Hawaii]], U.S.)}} | [[Duke Farms]] {{small|([[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]], U.S.)}} | [[New York City, New York]], U.S. | [[Rough Point]] {{small| ([[Newport, Rhode Island]], U.S.)\n}} }}\n}}\n| spouse        = {{plainlist|\n*{{marriage|[[James H. R. Cromwell]]|1935|1943|end=divorced}}\n*{{marriage|[[Porfirio Rubirosa]]|1947|1951|end=divorced}}\n}}\n| children      = 1\n}}\n\n'''Doris Duke''' (November 22, 1912 \u2013 October 28, 1993) was a billionaire tobacco heiress and philanthropist. A reluctant celebrity, her bittersweet life was famously woven of luxury, disputes and interludes of deep unhappiness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/29/obituaries/doris-duke-80-heiress-whose-great-wealth-couldn-t-buy-happiness-is-dead.html|title=Doris Duke, 80, Heiress Whose Great Wealth Couldn't Buy Happiness, Is Dead|last=Pace|first=Eric|date=October 29, 1993|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 14, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nDuke's passions varied wildly. Briefly a news correspondent in the 1940s, she also played jazz piano and learned to surf competitively. At her father's estate at [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]], she created one of America's largest indoor botanical displays. She was also active in preserving more than 80 historic buildings in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].\n\nTwice divorced, Duke enjoyed a colorful private life that was seldom out of the gossip columns.\n\nHer philanthropic work in [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] research, medicine, and child welfare continued into her old age. Her estimated $1.3 billion fortune was largely left to charity. Duke's legacy is now administered by the [http://ddcf.org Doris Duke Charitable Foundation], dedicated to medical research, prevention of cruelty to children and animals, the performing arts, wildlife and ecology.\n\n==Early life==\nDuke was born in New York City, the only child of [[tobacco]] and [[hydroelectric power]] tycoon [[James Buchanan Duke]] and his second wife, Nanaline Holt Inman, widow of William Patterson Inman.{{sfn|Valentine|1987|p=9}} At his death in 1925, the elder Duke's will bequeathed the majority of his estate to his wife and daughter,<ref name=jbdukewill>{{cite news |title=James B. Duke Wills Bulk of $100,000,000 to Widow and Child |date= October 24, 1925 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 | work = [[The New York Times]] |page=1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/10/24/archives/james-b-duke-wills-bulk-of-100000000-to-widow-and-child-leaves.html}}</ref> along with $17 million in two separate clauses of the will, to [[The Duke Endowment]] he had created in 1924.<ref name=jbdukewill/> The total value of the estate was estimated variously at $60 million<ref name=suitfiled>{{cite news |title=Sues to Untangle J. B. Duke's Will |date=December 21, 1926 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 | work = [[The New York Times]] |page=17 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/12/21/archives/sues-to-untangle-jb-dukes-will-daughter-in-a-friendly-action-fights.html}}</ref> to $100 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|60|1925|r=0|fmt=c}} million to ${{Inflation|US|.1|r=3|1925|fmt=c}} billion in {{#time:Y}}), the majority derived from J.B. Duke's holdings in the [[American Tobacco Company]].<ref name=twins>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/billionaire-twins-abused-slaves-doris-duke-heir-father/story?id=19853671|work=ABC|title=Billionaire Twins Abused Like Slaves by Dad|author=James, Susan Donaldson|date=August 5, 2013|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuke spent her early childhood at [[Duke Farms]], her father's {{convert|2700|acre|km2|adj=on}} estate in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]].<ref name=suitsettled>{{cite news |title=Girl of 14 to Run 3,000 Acre Estate | work = [[The New York Times]] |date=September 25, 1927 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 |page=E1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/09/25/archives/girl-of-14-to-run-3000acre-estate-daughter-of-the-late-james-b-duke.html}}</ref> Due to ambiguity in James Duke's will, a lawsuit was filed in 1927 to prevent auctions and outright sales of real estate he had owned; in effect, Doris Duke successfully sued her mother and other executors to prevent the sales.<ref name=suitsettled/><ref>{{cite book  | last = Schwarz | first = Ted  | title = Trust No One: The Glamorous Life and Bizarre Death of Doris Duke  | publisher = Vivisphere Publishing  | year = 1997   | isbn = 978-1-892323-17-0}}</ref> One of the pieces of real estate in question was [[James B. Duke House|a Manhattan mansion at 1 East 78th Street]]<ref name=suitsettled/> which later became the home of the [[Institute of Fine Arts]] at [[New York University]].\n\nWhen she turned 18, in 1930, the {{convert|6|ft|m|adj=on}}<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chloesorvino/2014/07/10/how-lavish-addiction-fueled-spending-dwindled-the-duke-family-fortune/#352b93ed68b3|work=Forbes|title=The Duke Family Fortune: Depleted By Lavish, Addiction-Fueled Spending?|author=Sorvino, Chloe|date=July 10, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> tall Duke was presented to society as a [[debutante]], at a ball at [[Rough Point]], the family residence in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Doris Duke Feted at Newport Dance | work = [[The New York Times]] |date= August 24, 1930 |accessdate=July 25, 2010 |page=N8 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/08/24/archives/doris-duke-feted-at-newport-dance-daughter-of-mrs-james-b-duke-is.html}}</ref> She received large bequests from her father's will when she turned 21, 25, and 30; she was sometimes referred to as the \"world's richest girl.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Doris Duke World's Richest Girl at Stroke of Midnight |date=November 21, 1933 |work=Washington Post |page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Police Guard Richest Girl |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |page=4 |date=January 22, 1934}}</ref> Her mother died in 1962, leaving her jewelry and a coat.<ref>{{Cite news |title=US News |work=[[Time Magazine]] |date=June 29, 1962 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,897953,00.html |quote=All but passed over in the latest parceling was Skipper's Aunt Doris Duke\u2014Nanaline's daughter\u2014already worth an estimated $70 million, who was merely bequeathed some of her mother's jewelry. When auctioned off by Christies several years ago, those pieces of jewelry, which included a 20 carat diamond ring from Tiffany & Co., fetched over $4,000.000. |accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Adult life==\nWhen Duke came of age, she used her wealth to pursue a variety of interests, including extensive world travel and the arts. During [[World War II]], she worked in a canteen for sailors in [[Egypt]], taking a [[One-dollar salary|salary of one dollar a year]].<ref name=nytobit>{{cite news |author=Pace, Eric |title=Doris Duke, 80, Heiress Whose Great Wealth Couldn't Buy Happiness, Is Dead |work=[[The New York Times]] | date=October 28, 1993 |accessdate=May 7, 2008 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/29/obituaries/doris-duke-80-heiress-whose-great-wealth-couldn-t-buy-happiness-is-dead.html}}</ref> She spoke French fluently.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inventory of the Doris Duke Papers, 1798-2003 and undated (Duke University Libraries)|url=http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/uadukedoris|website=Library.duk.edu|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}</ref> In 1945, Duke began a short-lived career as a foreign correspondent for the [[International News Service]], reporting from different cities across the war-ravaged Europe. After the war, she moved to Paris and wrote for the magazine ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]''.\n\nWhile living in Hawaii, Duke became the first non-Hawaiian woman to take up competitive surfing under the tutelage of surfing champion and Olympic swimmer [[Duke Kahanamoku]] and his brothers.<ref name=pony/> A lover of animals, in particular her dogs and pet camels, in her later years Duke became a [[wildlife refuge]] supporter.\n\nDuke's interest in [[horticulture]] led to a friendship with [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author and scientific farmer [[Louis Bromfield]], who operated Malabar Farm, his country home in [[Lucas, Ohio|Lucas]], [[Ohio]] in [[Richland County, Ohio|Richland County]]. Today, his farm is part of [[Malabar Farm State Park]], made possible by a donation from Duke that helped purchase the property after Bromfield's death. A section of woods there is dedicated to her and bears her name.\n\nAt age 46, Duke started to create [[Duke Gardens (New Jersey)|Duke Gardens]], an exotic public-display garden, to honor her father James Buchanan Duke.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.njskylands.com/atdukgar.htm|title=The Gardens at Duke Farms| publisher=Skylands Visitor Guide|accessdate=June 2, 2008}}</ref> She extended new [[greenhouse]]s from the [[Horace Trumbauer]] conservatory<ref name=\"New Greenhouse\">{{cite web| url=http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=282|title=New Greenhouse | publisher=Duke Farms|accessdate=May 7, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070622073346/http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=282 |archivedate = June 22, 2007}}</ref> at her home in [[Duke Farms]], New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=4|title=History | publisher=Duke Farms|accessdate=February 11, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080111134008/http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=4 |archivedate = January 11, 2008}}</ref> Each of the eleven interconnected gardens was a full-scale re-creation of a garden theme, country or period, inspired by DuPont's [[Longwood Gardens]]. She designed the architectural, artistic and botanical elements of the displays based on observations from her extensive international travels.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://wirednewyork.com/forum/showthread.php?t=3779|title=A Great Estate Opens Its Gates| publisher=wired|accessdate=May 10, 2008}}</ref> She also labored on their installation, sometimes working 16-hour days.<ref name=nytobit/> Display construction began in 1958.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=300}}\n\nDuke had learned to play the piano at an early age and developed a lifelong appreciation of [[jazz]] and befriended jazz musicians. She also liked [[gospel music]] and sang in a gospel choir.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nDuke cultivated an extensive art collection, principally of [[Islamic art|Islamic]] and [[Southeast Asian art|Southeast Asian]] art. In 2014, sixty objects from her collection (including ceramics, textiles, paintings, tile panels, and full-scale architectural elements) were displayed temporarily at the [[University of Michigan Museum of Art]] in the exhibition \"Doris Duke's Shangri La: Architecture, Landscape, and Islamic Art,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://umma.umich.edu/exhibitions/2014/doris-duke-s-shangri-la-architecture-landscape-and-islamic-art|title=Doris Duke's Shangri La: Architecture, Landscape, and Islamic Art {{!}} University of Michigan Museum of Art|website=umma.umich.edu|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> organized by the Doris Duke Foundation for Islamic Art.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://umma.umich.edu/exhibitions/2014/doris-duke-s-shangri-la-architecture-landscape-and-islamic-art|title=Doris Duke's Shangri La: Architecture, Landscape, and Islamic Art {{!}} University of Michigan Museum of Art|website=umma.umich.edu|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> The collection is on public display at her former home in [[Honolulu, Hawaii]], now the [[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Museum of Islamic Art, Culture, & Design]].<ref>https://www.ddcf.org/about-us/about-doris-duke/</ref><ref>https://www.vogue.com/article/doris-duke-shangri-la-house-hawaii</ref>\n\nIn 1966, Duke was behind the wheel of a rented car when it lurched forward and crushed interior designer [[Eduardo Tirella]] as he was opening the gates of the mansion they were restoring in Newport, Rhode Island. While it was ruled a freak accident by the police, Tirella's family sued and won $75,000 when Duke was found negligent.<ref>{{cite news|last=McPhillips|first=Jody|last2=MacKay|first2=Scott|title=Doris Duke had it all -- and now her foundation is giving a lot back|url=http://www.projo.com/specials/century/month9/0961.htm|accessdate=March 22, 2011|newspaper=The Providence Journal|date=September 26, 1999}}</ref>\n\n===Homes===\n[[File:Italian Garden at Duke Gardens.jpg|thumb|Duke created the Italian Garden to showcase sculptures that her father had collected, such as this replica of Canova's Three Graces]]\nDuke acquired a number of homes. Her principal residence and official domicile<ref name=\"courttv.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html |title=court TV becomes truTV |publisher=Courttv.com |accessdate=March 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914172504/http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html |archivedate=September 14, 2008  }}</ref> was [[Duke Farms]], her father's 2,700 acre (11&nbsp;km\u00b2) estate in [[Hillsborough Township, New Jersey]]. Here she created [[Duke Gardens (New Jersey)|Duke Gardens]], a {{convert|60000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} public indoor botanical display that was among the largest in America.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Garmey  | first = Jane   | title = Doris Duke's Storied Gardens Are No More  | newspaper = Wall Street Journal  | pages =   | date = May 28, 2008   | accessdate = May 28, 2008  | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121192910041724297#  | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nDuke's other residences were private during her lifetime: she spent summer weekends working on her [[Newport Restoration Foundation]] projects while staying at [[Rough Point]], the 49-room English manor-style mansion that she inherited in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=364}}\n\nWinters were spent at an estate she built in the 1930s and named \"[[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Shangri La]]\" in [[Honolulu, Hawaii]];{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=210}} and at \"[[Falcon Lair]]\" in [[Beverly Hills, California]],{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=270}} once the home of [[Rudolph Valentino]]. She also maintained two apartments in [[Manhattan]]: a nine-room penthouse with a {{convert|1000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} veranda at 475 Park Avenue that is currently owned by journalist [[Cindy Adams]];<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Swanson|first1=Carl|title=Only on Park Avenue, Kids|newspaper=New York Magazine|date=June 5, 2000|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/realestate/features/3364}}</ref> and another apartment near [[Times Square]] that she used exclusively as an office for the management of her financial affairs.\n\nShe purchased her own [[Boeing 737]] jet and redecorated the interior to travel between homes and on her trips to collect art and plants. The plane included a bedroom decorated to resemble a bedroom in a real house. Doris Duke had difficulty remaining in one place, and whenever she arrived somewhere, she had the desire to go somewhere else.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aimeedeheeren.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 20, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110142857/http://www.aimeedeheeren.com/ |archivedate=January 10, 2015  }}</ref>\n\nDuke was a hands-on homeowner, climbing a ladder to a three-story scaffolding to clean tile murals in the courtyard of Shangri La,<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Kam |first1=Nadine |title=Fantasyland |newspaper=Honolulu Star Bulletin |date=November 3, 2002 |url=http://starbulletin.com/2002/11/03/features/story1.htm |format=\u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AFantasyland&as_publication=&as_ylo=2002&as_yhi=2002&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>  }}{{dead link|date=January 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> and working side by side with her gardeners at Duke Farms.\n\nThree of Duke's residences are currently managed by subsidiaries of the [[Doris Duke Charitable Foundation]] and allow limited public access. Duke Farms in New Jersey is managed by the Duke Farms Foundation; a video tour of the former Duke Gardens is available. Rough Point was deeded to the [[Newport Restoration Foundation]] in 1999 and opened to the public in 2000. Tours are limited to 12 people. Shangri-La is operated by the [[Doris Duke Foundation for Islamic Art]]; small personal tours and an online virtual tour are available.<ref>[http://www.shangrilahawaii.org/page.asp?pageId=5] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619070048/http://www.shangrilahawaii.org/page.asp?pageId=5 |date=June 19, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{more citations needed section|date=October 2016}}\n[[File:James H. R. and Doris Cromwell.jpg|thumb|Duke with then husband [[James H. R. Cromwell]] in January 1940]]\nDuke married twice, the first time in 1935 to [[James H. R. Cromwell]], the son of [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]] society doyenne Eva Stotesbury.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=132}} Cromwell, a [[New Deal]] advocate like his wife, used her fortune to finance his political career. In 1940 he served several months as U.S. Ambassador to Canada and ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate. The couple had a daughter, Arden, who died one day after her birth.{{efn|Duke's only biological child, Arden Cromwell, was born prematurely on July 13, 1940 in Hawaii. Arden died one day later on July 14.<ref>{{cite news|title=Doris Duke's Premature Baby Dies After Living for 24 Hours|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 14, 1940|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cromwell Baby Dies|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 14, 1940|accessdate=July 25, 2010|page=16|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1940/07/14/archives/cromwell-baby-dies-child-born-to-former-doris-duke-lives-only-24.html}}</ref>}}{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=257}} They divorced in 1943.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|pages=199, 213\u201314}}\n\nOn September 1, 1947, while in Paris, Duke became the third wife of [[Porfirio Rubirosa]], a diplomat from the [[Dominican Republic]].{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=232}} She reportedly paid his second wife, actress [[Danielle Darrieux]], $1 million to agree to an uncontested divorce. Because of her great wealth, Duke's marriage to Rubirosa attracted the attention of the [[U.S. State Department]], which cautioned her against using her money to promote a political agenda. Further, there was concern that in the event of her death, a foreign government could gain too much leverage. Therefore, Rubirosa had to sign a [[pre-nuptial agreement]]; during the marriage, though, she gave Rubirosa several million dollars in gifts, including a stable of polo ponies, sports cars, a converted [[B-25]] bomber, and, in the divorce settlement, a 17th-century house in Paris. One of Doris Duke's best friends was Brazilian socialite and \"jetsetter\" [[Aim\u00e9e de Heeren]].\n\nShe reportedly had numerous affairs, with, among others, [[Duke Kahanamoku]], [[Errol Flynn]], [[Alec Cunningham-Reid]], General [[George S. Patton]], [[Joe Castro (musician)|Joe Castro]], and [[Louis Bromfield]].{{efn|Duke had numerous lovers, as documented by biographer Stephanie Mansfield; these include Duke Kahanamoku{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=257}} and Errol Flynn.{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=210}}{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|p=217}}{{sfn|Mansfield|1999|pages=229\u201331}}<ref name=pony>{{cite book|author=Pony Duke|title=Too Rich. Family Secrets of Doris Duke|publisher=HarperCollins, 1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/toorichfamilysec00duke/page/104 104ff]|isbn=0-06-017218-5|url=https://archive.org/details/toorichfamilysec00duke/page/104|year=1996}}</ref>}}\n\nDuke posted a bail of $5,000,000 for her friend, former Philippine [[First Lady]] [[Imelda Marcos]] after the latter was arrested for racketeering.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/11/03/world/doris-duke-offers-mrs-marcos-s-bail.html|title=DORIS DUKE OFFERS MRS. MARCOS'S BAIL|last=Bohlen|first=Celestine|date=November 3, 1988|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 8, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn 1992, at the age of 79, Duke had a [[Rhytidectomy|facelift]]. She began trying to walk while she was still heavily medicated and fell, breaking her hip. In January 1993, she underwent surgery for a knee replacement. She was hospitalized from February 2 to April 15. She underwent a second knee surgery in July of that year.\n\nA day after returning home from this second surgery, she suffered a severe stroke. Doris Duke [[Harry Demopoulos#Duke Estate|died]] at her Falcon's Lair home on October 28, 1993, at the age of 80. The cause was progressive [[pulmonary edema]] resulting in [[cardiac arrest]], according to a spokesman.<ref name=\"courttv.com\"/><ref name=nytobit/>\n\nDuke was cremated 24 hours after her death and her executor, [[Bernard Lafferty]], scattered her ashes into the Pacific Ocean as her last will specified.<ref name=\"courttv.com\"/>\n\n==Net worth==\nWhen Doris' father died, he left a fortune valued at $100 million,<ref name=ny>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/02/nyregion/doris-duke-leaves-1-billion-to-a-new-charitable-foundation.html?pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|title=Doris Duke Leaves $1 billion to a New Charitable Foundation|date=November 2, 1993|author=McFadden, Robert|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> with the largest share going to Duke and her mother. Nanaline was a shrewd businesswoman, often compared to [[Hetty Green]], and when she died in 1962, she left her daughter an estate then estimated to be worth $250 million.<ref name=ny/>\n\nDuke also owned numerous shares in big-name companies, such as [[General Motors]], and had a large financial team of bankers and accountants to manage her holdings (since, despite rumors, Duke had little to no interest in money matters). In addition, Duke had a collection of artwork, which was said to include works by Picasso, Van Gogh, Rembrandt and Monet, as well as her valuable collection of Islamic and Southeast Asia art and furniture. Also in Duke's collection were over 2,000 bottles of rare wine (worth over $5 million) and the extraordinary Duke collection of fine jewels. Her total net worth, including all property, was valued at $5.3 billion.\n\n===Philanthropy===\nDuke's first major philanthropic act was to establish Independent Aid, Inc., in 1934, when she was 21 years old, in order to manage the many requests for financial assistance addressed to her.<ref>{{cite web| title=Doris Duke Biographical History and Archival Collections (Duke University Libraries)| url=http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/collections/people/dorisduke/#item-14| website=Library.duk.edu| accessdate=October 24, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906141800/http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/collections/people/dorisduke/#item-14| archive-date=September 6, 2013| url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1958, she established the [[Duke Gardens (New Jersey)|Duke Gardens]] Foundation to endow the public display gardens she started to create at Duke Farms. Her Foundation intended that Duke Gardens \"reveal the interests and philanthropic aspirations of the Duke family, as well as an appreciation for other cultures and a yearning for global understanding.\".<ref name=\"New Greenhouse\"/> Duke Gardens were the center of a controversy<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.savedukegardens.org |title=Duke Gardens, Then and Now |publisher=www.SaveDukeGardens.org |accessdate=March 22, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820103927/http://savedukegardens.org/ |archive-date=August 20, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> over the decision by the trustees of the [[Doris Duke Charitable Foundation]] to close them on May 25, 2008.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Duke Farms Promotes \"Greener\" Future |publisher=Duke Farms |date=March 2, 2008 |url=http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=523 |accessdate=April 14, 2008 |quote=it\u2019s the final months of the gardens being on display in the greenhouses that have enchanted visitors since 1964 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328065214/http://www.dukefarms.org/page.asp?pageId=523 |archivedate=March 28, 2008  }}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, Duke created the [[Newport Restoration Foundation]] with the goal of [[historic preservation|preserving]] more than eighty colonial buildings in the town. Historic properties include [[Rough Point]], [[Samuel Whitehorne House]], [[Prescott Farm]], the Buloid-Perry House, the King's Arms Tavern, the Baptist Meetinghouse, and the  Cotton House. Seventy-one buildings are rented to tenants. Only five function as museums. She also funded the construction of [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]]'s ashram in India, [[The Beatles at Rishikesh|visited by the Beatles]] in 1968.<ref name=NCH>{{cite book|title=Beyond Gurus: A Woman of Many Worlds|first=Nancy Cooke|last=de Herrera|publisher=Blue Dolphin Publishing|year=1993|isbn=978-0-931892-49-3|url=https://archive.org/details/beyondguruswoman00herr}}</ref> \n  \nDuke's extensive travels led to an interest in a variety of cultures, and during her lifetime she amassed a considerable collection of Islamic and Southeast Asian art. After her death, numerous pieces were donated to The [[Asian Art Museum of San Francisco|Asian Art Museum]] of San Francisco and the [[Walters Art Museum]] of Baltimore.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tingley|first=Nancy|title=Doris Duke: The Southeast Asian Art Collection|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|pages=93\u201394|isbn=978-0-8248-2773-1|year=2003}}</ref>\n\nDuke did much additional philanthropic work and was a major benefactor of medical research and child welfare programs. In the late 1980s, Duke donated $2 million to Duke University to be used for [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] research.<ref name=ny/> Her foundation, Independent Aid, became the Doris Duke Foundation, which still exists as a private grant-making entity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inventory of the Doris Duke Foundation Records, 1934-2009 (Duke University Libraries)|accessdate=October 23, 2016|url=http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/dorisdukefound|website=Library.duk.edu}}</ref> After her death, the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation was established in 1996, supporting four national grant making programs and Doris Duke's three estates, [[Shangri La (Doris Duke)|Shangri La]], [[Rough Point]], and [[Duke Farms]].\n\n===Trusts and wills===\nDuke was the life beneficiary of two trusts created by her father, James Buchanan Duke, in 1917 and 1924. The income from the trusts was payable to any children after her death. In 1988, at the age of 75, Duke legally adopted a woman named Chandi Heffner, then a 35-year-old [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness|Hare Krishna]] devotee and sister of the third wife of billionaire [[Nelson Peltz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,164455,00.html |title=Sarandon to Play World's Richest Little Girl |publisher=[[Fox News]] |date=August 2, 2005 |accessdate=October 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606201655/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,164455,00.html |archive-date=June 6, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Duke initially maintained that Heffner was the reincarnation of her only biological child Arden, who died soon after birth in 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|title=Top Three Inheritance Disputes|publisher=legalzoom|accessdate=May 10, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411060518/http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|archive-date=April 11, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe two women had a falling out, and the final version of Duke's will specified that she did not wish Heffner to benefit from her father's trusts; she also negated the adoption. Despite the negation, after Duke's death, the estate's trustees settled a lawsuit brought by Heffner for $65 million.<ref name=\"Top Three Inheritance Disputes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|title=Top Three Inheritance Disputes|publisher=legalzoom|accessdate=June 29, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411060518/http://www.legalzoom.com/legal-articles/article15046.html|archive-date=April 11, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn her final will, Duke left virtually all of her fortune to several existing and new charitable foundations. She appointed her butler, [[Bernard Lafferty]] born in [[Creeslough]], [[County Donegal]], [[Ireland]], as executor of her estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-11-05/news/mn-61438_1_butler-made-wealthy-by-heiress|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Butler Made Wealthy by Heiress Dies|date=November 5, 1996|author=Lieberman, Paul|accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref> Lafferty appointed the [[U. S. Trust]] company as corporate co-executor. Lafferty and Duke's friend Marion Oates Charles were named as her trustees.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dukeminier|first=Jesse|title=Wills, Trusts, and Estates|publisher = Aspen Publishers|pages=93\u201394}}</ref>\n\nHowever a number of lawsuits were filed against the will. At death, Duke's fortune was estimated at upwards of $1.2 billion.<ref name=ny/> The best-known lawsuit<ref name=\"nytimes1996\">{{cite news|last=Van Natta|first=Dan|title=Deal Reached over the Estate of Doris Duke|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 11, 1996|accessdate=May 7, 2008|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F02E5D91039F932A25757C0A960958260}}</ref> was initiated by [[Harry Demopoulos]]. In an earlier will, Demopoulos had been named executor <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/05/nyregion/bernard-lafferty-the-butler-for-doris-duke-dies-at-51.html|title=Bernard Lafferty the Butler for Doris Dukes Dies at 51|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}</ref> and challenged Lafferty's appointment. Demopolous argued that Lafferty and his lawyers had cajoled a sick, sedated old woman into giving him control of her estate.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nEven more sensational accusations were made by a nurse, Tammy Payette, who contended that Lafferty and a prominent Beverly Hills physician, Dr. Charles Kivowitz, had conspired to hasten Duke's death with morphine and Demerol.  In 1996, the year Lafferty died, the Los Angeles [[District Attorney]]'s office ruled there was no firm evidence of foul play.<ref name=\"Top Three Inheritance Disputes\"/>\n\n[[Duke University]] also filed suit, claiming entitlement to a larger share of the Duke assets than the $10 million provided in the will (although Duke's will also stated that any beneficiary who disputed its provisions should receive nothing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|title=Last Will of Duke, Section 19|publisher=Court TV|accessdate=September 10, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914172504/http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|archivedate=September 14, 2008}}</ref>).\n\nLitigation involving 40 lawyers at 10 different law firms tied up the Duke estate for nearly three years. New York courts ultimately removed Lafferty for using estate funds for his own support and US Trust for failing \"to do anything to stop him.\"<ref name=\"Top Three Inheritance Disputes\"/> The [[Surrogate Court]] of Manhattan overrode Duke's will and appointed new trustees from among those who had challenged it: [[Harry Demopoulos]]; J. Carter Brown (later also involved in overturning the will of [[Albert C. Barnes]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barneswatch.org/menu_matisse.html |title=Untitled Document |accessdate=September 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090116035542/http://www.barneswatch.org/menu_matisse.html |archivedate=January 16, 2009  }}</ref>); Marion Oates Charles, the sole trustee from Duke's last will; James Gill, a lawyer; [[Nannerl O. Keohane]], president of Duke University; and [[John J. Mack]], president of [[Morgan Stanley]].<ref name=\"nytimes1996\"/> The fees for their lawsuits exceeded $10 million, and were paid by the Duke estate. These trustees now control all assets of the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation, which Doris Duke directed should support medical research, anti-vivisectionism, prevention of cruelty to children and animals, performance arts, wildlife, and ecology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|title=Last Will of Doris Duke, Section 8|publisher=Court TV|accessdate=September 10, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914172504/http://www.courttv.com/archive/legaldocs/newsmakers/wills/duke.html|archivedate=September 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe DDCF also controls funding for the three separate foundations created to operate Duke's former homes: the Doris Duke Foundation for Islamic Art, Duke Farms and Newport Restoration Foundation. The trustees have progressively reduced funding for these foundations, stating that Doris Duke's own works are \"perpetuating the Duke family history of personal passions and conspicuous consumption.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sudol |first=Valerie |title=Famed Duke Gardens To Become Ambitious 'Green' Lab |newspaper=Newhouse News Service |year=2008 |accessdate=May 6, 2008 |url=http://www.newhouse.com/famed-duke-gardens-to-become-ambitious-green-laboratory-4.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928021113/http://www.newhouse.com/famed-duke-gardens-to-become-ambitious-green-laboratory-4.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 28, 2008 }}</ref> Recently, these foundations have sold some assets<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newportrestoration.com/pr/CarpetSale08.html|title=Sale of Rare Carpet to Benefit Newport Restoration Foundation Collections Fund|publisher=Newport Restoration Foundation|accessdate=June 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921162758/http://www.newportrestoration.com/pr/CarpetSale08.html|archive-date=September 21, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> and have closed Duke Gardens. Christie's, New York, published a heavily illustrated catalog of over 600 pages for its auction of \"The Doris Duke Collection, sold to benefit the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation\" which was held in New York City over three days in 2004.\n\nThe last living heirs to Duke's vast Industrial Age fortune are twins Georgia Inman and Walker \u201cPatterson\u201d Inman III, 21, the children of Walker Inman Jr., Duke's nephew. Their childhood has been documented as a tragedy of grotesque neglect, abuse, parental violence and addiction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/the-poorest-rich-kids-in-the-world-80712/|title=The Poorest Rich Kids in the World|last=Erdely|first=Sabrina Rubin|last2=Erdely|first2=Sabrina Rubin|date=August 12, 2013|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.drphil.com/shows/2159/|title=The Darkness of Riches: Born Billionaires but Starved, Neglected and Locked in a Basement|date=January 30, 2014|website=Dr. Phil|language=en-US|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nSeveral biographies of Duke have been published, notably:\n\n* Stephanie Mansfield's ''The Richest Girl in The World'' (Putnam 1994). \n* Pony Duke, her disinherited nephew, and Jason Thomas published ''Too Rich: The Family Secrets of Doris Duke'' (1996).\n* Ted Schwarz with Tom Rybak, co-authored by one of Duke's staff, ''Trust No One'' (1997).\n* Sallie Bingham's ''The Silver Swan: In Search of Doris Duke'' (2020).\n\nSeveral films/television shows has been made about her life, including:\n\n* A four-hour made-for-television mini-series, based on Mansfield's book, (starring [[Lauren Bacall]] as Duke and [[Richard Chamberlain]] as Lafferty) was aired with the title, ''[[Too Rich: The Secret Life of Doris Duke]]'' (1999)\n* Her life is also the subject of the [[HBO]] film ''[[Bernard and Doris]]'', starring [[Susan Sarandon]] as Duke and [[Ralph Fiennes]] as the butler Lafferty.\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{Cite book|last=Mansfield|first=Stephanie|year=1999|title=The Richest Girl in the World: The Extravagant Life and Fast Times of Doris Duke|publisher=Kensington Publishing Corporation|isbn=978-0-786-01027-1|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/richestgirlinwor00kens}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Valentine|first=Tom|year=1987|title=Daddy's Duchess: The Unauthorized Biography of Doris Duke|publisher=L. Stuart|isbn=978-0-818-40443-6|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/daddysduchessuna00vale}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Cohen |first1=Alina |title=The Eccentric Heiress Who Lived Inside an Epic Monument To Islamic Art |work=[[Artsy]] |date=November 10, 2017 |url=https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-eccentric-heiress-lived-inside-epic-monument-islamic-art |accessdate=November 12, 2017  }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.ddcf.org Doris Duke Charitable Foundation]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130307035225/http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/collections/people/dorisduke/ Doris Duke Biographical History and Archival Collections (Duke University Libraries)]\n*Thomas D. Mcavoy: [https://images.google.com/hosted/life/l?imgurl=85c43220269edd75&q=source:life James Cromwell, Doris Duke and Frank Murphy attending Jackson Day dinner] (Washington DC, 1940)\n*{{Find a Grave|5586|accessdate=August 30, 2010}}\n{{Rhode Island Women's Hall of Fame}}\n